      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                  <name type="place" ref="./Placeography.xml#Black-Castle_IE">Black Castle</name>
                  <date></date></dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>
                     <!-- Use if letter has a saluation ("Dear Sir," for example). If not, delete this line.-->
                     My dear Sir
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
              <placeName type="place" ref="./Placeography.xml#Black-Castle_IE">Black Castle</placeName>near<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline"><placeName type="place" ref="./Placeography.xml#Navan_IE">Navan<placeName></hi><lb/>
               
              <p>It is impossible that any<lb/>
               black marks I can make<lb/>
               upon paper can convey to<lb/>
               you the idea of the concern<lb/>
               I feel for these changes —<lb/></p>
               
               <p>It is not for you or for <persName type="person" ref="./Personography.xml#LansH1">Lord Lansdowne</persName><lb/>
               Lansdowne that I feel but
               for <placeName type="place" ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> — the loss of place<lb/>
               and power may for aught<lb/>
               I know may be again of <choice><orig>happi-<lb/>
               ness</orig><reg>happiness</reg></choice> to you both — But the<lb/>
               loss to <placeName type="place" ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> of such friends<lb/>
               in power is I fear irremedia<lb/>
               'ble — I have much that I wish<lb/>
               to say to you, which I cannot<lb/>
               &amp; ought not to put on paper<lb/>
               — for instance - circumstances<lb/>
               I have privately learned from<lb/>
               catholics respecting late distur<lb/>
               bances in this Town of <placeName type="place" ref="./Placeography.xml#Navan_IE">Navan</placeName><lb/>
               — and elsewhere —<lb/></p>
               
               <p>The hand of despotism<lb/>
               may press down &amp; [underline]keep[/underline] down<lb/>
               a nation if that hand be strong<lb/>
               enough — But the hand must<lb/>
               <del>be</del> in that case <hi rend="underline">never be removed</hi><lb/>
               &amp; must never relax —<lb/>
               To the conqueror of Waterloo<lb/>
               The [underline]reco[/underline]nquest of <placeName type="place" ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName> would<lb/>
               appear &amp; be easy perhaps; &amp; there<lb/>
               fore his [unclear]mil[superscript]n[/superscript][/unclear] genius may brave<lb/>
               &amp; despise the danger of putting<lb/>
               things to this issue — But — after<lb/>
               wards — he must be prepared<lb/>
               to exterminate - he can<lb/>
               no otherwise extinguish [insertion]public[/insertion] opinion<lb/></p>
            
               <p><persName type="person" ref="./Personography.xml#CromO1">Cromwell</persName>— who was better<lb/>
               made for the purpose than<lb/>
               any other man stopped short<lb/>
               of the mark &amp; after wading<lb/>
               through slaughter to his<lb/>
               church left 50,000 to tell<lb/>
               the tale —<lb/></p>
            
               <p>But I have no business with<lb/>
               these things --<lb/>
               NB. I do not think from what I have<lb/>
               heard that the priests would dare<lb/>
               to let themselves be paid by Govt<lb/>
               unless [unclear][underline]Cat - eman[/underline][/unclear]. were same time granted<lb/>
               — Great debating may be upon the means<lb/>
               &amp; tenets of said words — we shall hear from<lb/>
               the Pope I suppose soon — &amp; from you? — When?<lb/></p>
            
               <p>You were so very kind to<lb/>
               my brother <persName type="person" ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName>— another<lb/>
               brother of mine — [underline]<persName type="person" ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeC1">Sneyd</persName>[/underline] E —<lb/>
               now begs me to recal him</lb> 
               to your memory — These are<lb/>
               his words<lb/></p>
            
               <p>"Now that<persName type="person" ref="./Personography.xml#SpriT1">Spring Rice</persName> is not in<lb/>
               "office can you <persName type="person" ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">D[superscript]r[/superscript]. Maria give me</persName><lb/>
               "a pretext for calling on him —<lb/>
               "I should like much to renew my<lb/>
               "acquaintance with one whom<lb/>
               "I foresaw would be a distinguished<lb/>
               "man when I met him at <persName type="person" ref="./Personography.xml#SmedE1">Edward</persName><lb/>
               "Smedley's chambers at <placeName type="place" ref="./Placeography.xml#Trinity-College_IE">Trinity</placeName>"<lb/></p>
               
               <p>It will gratify me and<lb/>
               my brother much if you can<lb/>
               give him half an hour of<lb/>
               your conversation — I enclose<lb/>
               a note for him — Send it by<lb/>
               2[superscript]d[/superscript] post. It contains a little note<lb/>
               of introduction for him to you<lb/>
               which is all I can do for him<lb/></p>
            
               <p>He is a more literary man<lb/>
               than <persName type="person" ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">William</persName> &amp; having seen<lb/>
               a great deal of the world<lb/>
               abroad for many years has<lb/>
               more that will make half an<lb/>
               hour's conversation agreeable<lb/>
               to you — Oblige me — and I shall<lb/>
               be obliged — which is more than<lb/>
               many people who ask favors<lb/>
               [underline]can promise[/underline] or at least more<lb/>
               than they are often found to per<lb/>
               form<lb/></p>
               
               <p>I am Yours very sincerely<lb/>
               <persName type="person" ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <date>Feb 8[superscript]th[/superscript]1828</date>
               MA3038.3
               
               
